⁵ Libyphoenices were those su bjects of Carthage who had sprung from marriages between the immigrant Phoenicians and native Africans. They ranked next, therefore, to the proper Carthaginians, the ruling Phoenician citizens of the capital, and probably inhabited the smaller towns in the Carthaginian territory.

⁶ The Ilergetes were a considerable Spanish tribe on this side of the Iberus, in the modern district of Catalonia. Their chief town was Ilerda (now Lerida). This little band of two hundred cavalry had no doubt volunteered for pay imo the Carthaginian service, sor their tribe was not subject to Carthage.
